    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Wrigley Names Agencies for China</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Allison Fass</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Fass, Allison</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Wm Wrigley Jr Co names offices of Leo Burnett Co and Starcom Worldwide to handle creative media duties for Wrigley brands in China; billings estimated at $18 million to $20 million (Advertising column) (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The Wm. Wrigley Jr. Company in Chicago said yesterday that it had named offices of the Leo Burnett Company and Starcom Worldwide, both part of the B Com3  Group, to handle the creative and media duties for Wrigley brands in China. Billings were estimated at $18 million to $20 million.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>The Wm. Wrigley Jr. Company in Chicago said yesterday that it had named offices of the Leo Burnett Company and Starcom Worldwide, both part of the B Com3  Group, to handle the creative and media duties for Wrigley brands in China. Billings were estimated at $18 million to $20 million.</p>
        <p>The decision came after a monthlong review that had been narrowed to Burnet, Starcom and offices of three other agencies: DDB Worldwide, part of the Omnicom Group; D'Arcy Masius Benton &amp; Bowles, another unit of B Com3 ; and Grey Advertising. DDB and Grey were the incumbents.</p>
        <p>THE MEDIA BUSINESS: ADVERTISING -- ADDENDA</p>
      </block>
